A meniscus is the rising of a fluid at its interface with a container. In the figure below, we zoom in on the side view of water in a rectangular container. \begin{center}
        \includegraphics[scale=0.2]{meniscus}
    \end{center}
    For water of density $\rho$ and surface tension $\sigma$, what is the height $h$ of its meniscus? Assume at the contact point with the container, the meniscus is perfectly vertical, i.e. it makes an angle $0^\circ$ to the container surface.

solution:
We balance horizontal forces on the part of the water that is above the surface.
    \begin{center}
        \includegraphics[scale=0.2]{soel2}
    \end{center}For a section of the meniscus a distance $\ell$ into the page, the force of surface tension pulls to the right with magnitude $\sigma \ell$. The pressure in the water is lower than that of the air at an average value $\rho gh/2$, and this difference in pressure is applied to an area $h\ell$. Equating the two forces, $$\sigma \ell=\frac{\rho gh^2\ell}{2}\Rightarrow h=\boxed{\sqrt{\frac{2\sigma}{\rho g}}}$$

